description:
The fight to pass Amendment 69 is heating up and we want to be ready!

A recent Denver Chamber of Commerce poll showed that 55% of Coloradans will support 69 if they have a clear idea of its benefits. This will be our job!
We now have a team of professional campaign organizers to assure success. A major organizing meeting in Louisville has been planned:

Where: Louisville Public Library, 951 Spruce St., 80027 Park on east lot or enter underground parking from alley just west of library)
When: Saturday, 6/25 from 10-11:30 AM
What: We will organize around 5 key campaign elements:
  1. Telephone banks;
  2. Canvassing;
  3. Social and Media Communications;
  4. Speakers Bureau and outreach to small businesses, professionals, etc. ;
  5. Data collection, entry and utilization.

Question: Can you join us? If so, please RSVP to either:
Dr. Laird Cagan: E-M: lairdpcagan@gmail.com
Barry Karlin, E-M: vbkarlin@gmail.com

If you can't make this meeting, please E-M one of us to say which of the 5 task forces listed above you wish to work with. You can select more than one. (Please don't E-M regrets as this letter is being addressed to over 600 Boulder supporters.) 
Please look at our revised website, www.ColoradoCare.org, and see the up-dated booklet option. Please mark your calendar now and let us hear back from you ASAP

Our Western Slope Regional organizers, Jeriel and Joel, have constructed a clear, powerful, yet friendly, presentation that takes us through setting specific voter goals; ways to meet those goals; ways to organize our local teams; and how to use VAN effectively.  I attended the training session in Gunnison today and came away knowing that this is essential training for as many of us as possible. It gives us the direction we need to be effective.

If you are unable to attend Thursday afternoon, but could make a Friday morning training, we will schedule a second training while Joel and Jeriel are in town. Let me know. Additional training will occur around the state but the sooner we implement these ideas, the better, so if you can make it to Denver on Thursday or Friday, try to do so. 

Who should attend? Definitely anyone in a leadership role should attend.  Active volunteers who could potentially step into a leadership role at any level are also most welcome. description:
Where: The Tired House B&B
 CR 109 is located on Highway 50 between Dr. Erickson's dental office and Anderson Motor. Turn south on CR 109. After the dead end sign, turn left into 7135 residence/B&B.

 The local volunteer committee for ColoradoCare Yes! is hosting a Volunteer ColoradoCare Training followed by a Speakers Training for individuals who are interested in getting more involved in the initiative and educating others about ColoradoCare.

The primary purpose of the volunteer training is to provide information about ColoradoCare. Volunteers are needed to promote ColoradoCare education to friends, neighbors, businesses, and at various outreach venues. Prior to the November election, we need to increase our volunteer capacity so accurate information is disseminated to the public.

 An example of a volunteer activity: a 2- hour shift at either the Buena Vista or the Salida Farmers Market to provide ColoradoCare education through conversation and/or a ColoradoCare flyer or other printed materials. Each farmers market will have two volunteers, one at a table and the other circulating through the market. 

 An example of a speaker activity: speak to a local organization, church, business, or neighborhood group.

 Volunteers will also be needed for additional outreach venues that are being planned.

 We hope you will join us for a potluck dinner and training!

 Please RSVP to Joe Lyford: 719-221-6764 or joehlyfordjr@gmail.com
location: Tired House B&B, 7135 County Road 109, Salida

description:
Colorado Care will do for Coloradans what Medicare does for seniors.

T.R. Reid, author, filmmaker, one of the plans architects, and an international authority on healthcare, will answer all our questions about Colorado Care.  Colorado Care covers everyone, saves billions of dollars, and gets corporate insurance companies out from between you and your doctor.  Colorado Care is a citizens initiative that will appear on our statewide ballot in November, when we will have the opportunity to vote it into law.

Free and open to the public. RSVP required.

You may call Paula V. with questions at 720-346-3689.  Please RSVP to Paula by Saturday if you dont normally attend these Peace & Justice forums, so we can prepare enough lunch for all.
